<chapter>
  <title>Chapter 4 Questions</title>

  <section xml:id="sec-differentials">
    <title>Differentials</title>
    
    <exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-differentials-1-v1" component="proteus">
      <title>Why Tangent Lines Work</title>
      <statement>
          <p>Which statement best describes how a tangent line, <m>\ell(x)</m>, approximates <m>f(x)</m> at the point of tangency <m>(x_0,f(x_0))</m>?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p><m>\ell(x)</m> closely resembles the curve near <m>(x_0,f(x_0))</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Correct—the tangent line shares the same instantaneous rate of change, so it hugs the curve nearby.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\ell(x)</m> closely resembles the graph of <m>f(x)</m> for any <m>x</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Not true—tangent lines only approximate well near a given point (i.e., locally), not globally.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\ell(x)</m> exactly matches the curve near <m>(x_0,f(x_0))</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Not true—tangent lines only approximate well near a given point.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\ell(x)</m> is the most accurate approximation of <m>f(x)</m> near <m>(x_0,f(x_0))</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Not correct—the error grows as you move away from the tangent point.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-differentials-2-v1" component="proteus">
      <title>Linearization vs. Actual Change</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Match each symbol to its meaning in the context of linearization.</p>
        <p><em>Assume <m>c</m> is some value of <m>x</m>.</em></p>
      </statement>
      <cardsort>
        <match>
          <premise><me>\Delta y</me></premise>
          <premise><m>f(c+\Delta x) - f(c)</m></premise>
          <response>The true change in <m>y</m> when <m>x</m> changes</response>
        </match>
        <match>
          <premise><me>f'(c)\Delta x</me></premise>
          <response>The linear (approximate) change in <m>y</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
          <premise><me>\Delta x</me></premise>
          <response>A chosen small change in <m>x</m></response>
        </match>
        <match>
          <premise><me>f'(c)</me></premise>
          <response>The slope of the tangent line at <m>x=c</m></response>
        </match>
      </cardsort>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-differentials-3-v1" component="proteus">
      <title>Differential Notation</title>
      <statement correct="no">
        <p>The symbol <m>dy/dx</m> in differential notation is literally a fraction of two separate quantities, <m>dy</m> and <m>dx</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>False — <m>dy/dx</m> is one symbol for the derivative, not an actual fraction. The resemblance to a fraction is helpful but can be misleading.</p>
      </feedback>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="chkpt-diff-fill-in">
      <title>Complete the Linearization Formula</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Fill in the blanks to complete the formula for the linear approximation of <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x=c</m>.</p>
        <p><m>\ell(x) = </m> <fillin mode="math" answer="f(c)"/> + <fillin mode="math" answer="f'(c)"/> (<m>x</m> - <fillin mode="math" answer="c"/>)</p>
      </statement>
      <evaluation>
        <evaluate>
          <test correct="yes"><mathcmp answer="f(c)"/></test>
        </evaluate>
        <evaluate>
          <test correct="yes"><mathcmp answer="f'(c)"/></test>
        </evaluate>
        <evaluate>
          <test correct="yes"><mathcmp answer="c"/></test>
        </evaluate>
      </evaluation>
    </exercise>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-newton">
    <title>Newton's Method</title>

    <exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-newton-1-v1" component="proteus">
      <title>Understanding Newton's Update Formula</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x)</m> be a function of <m>x</m> and let <m>x_0</m> be some <m>x</m>-value. Match each expression on the left with its geometric meaning, on the right. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <cardsort>
        <match>
          <premise><me>(x_0, f(x_0))</me></premise>
          <response>A point on the graph of <m>f(x)</m>.</response>
        </match>
        <match>
          <premise><me>f'(x_0)</me></premise>
          <response>Slope of the tangent line passing through <m>(x_0, f(x_0))</m>.</response>
        </match>
        <match>
          <premise><me>y = f'(x_0)(x-x_0)+f(x_0)</me></premise>
          <response>Equation of the tangent line passing through <m>(x_0, f(x_0))</m>.</response>
        </match>
        <match>
          <premise><me>0 = f'(x_0)(x-x_0)-f(x_0)</me></premise>
          <response>First step in finding the <m>x</m>-intercept of a line (<em>setting <m>y=0</m></em>).</response>
        </match>
        <match>
          <premise><me>x = x_0 - \dfrac{f(x_0)}{f'(x_0)}</me></premise>
          <response>The (solved) <m>x</m>-intercept of the tangent line.</response>
        </match>
        <match>
          <premise><me>x_1 = x_0 - \dfrac{f(x_0)}{f'(x_0)}</me></premise>
          <response>First Approximation in Newton's Method.</response>
        </match>
      </cardsort>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-newton-2-v1" component="proteus">
      <title>The Role of the Initial Guess</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Which of the following is the best reason why Newton's Method succeeded even with the initial guess <m>x_0=1</m> not being very close to the root of <m>x^3-x^2-1=0</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement><p>Newton's Method always works no matter where you start.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Not true—sometimes it diverges. The success here was not guaranteed.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p>The tangent lines still led toward the root despite a rough initial guess.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Correct—Newton's Method is often robust to imperfect starting points.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>The derivative was zero at <m>x=1</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Incorrect—the derivative was not zero; a zero derivative would actually make Newton's Method fail.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-newton-2-v1" component="proteus">
      <title>Detecting a <q>Bad</q> Initial Guess</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Starting with an initial guess, <m>x_0</m>, suppose you compute the next value, <m>x_1</m>, in Newton's Method using the update formula:
          <me>x_{1} = x_{0} - \dfrac{f(x_{0})}{f'(x_{0})}</me>
          Which of the following might be an indication that you have a <q>bad</q> initial guess?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p>When computing <m>f'(x_0)</m>, you get a value very close to zero.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Yes, a very small <m>f'(x_0)</m> (i.e., denominator in the formula) usually leads to the next approximation being very far from the root.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p>The value of <m>x_1</m> is very far from <m>x_0</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Yes, this is a bad sign since it indicates that tangent line passes through a point near a <q>peak</q> or <q>valley</q> of <m>f(x)</m>.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>When computing <m>f'(x_1)</m> in the formula, you get a value near zero.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Since <m>f'(x_1)</m> is not in the formula for <m>x=x_0</m>, it shouldn't bepart of the calculation.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>When computing <m>f(x_0)</m> in the formula, you get a value near zero.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>No, this is actually a good sign since <m>x_0</m> is near the root and Newton's method will likely converge.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>The value of <m>x_1</m> is very close to <m>x_0</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>No, this is a good sign since the only way this could happen is if <m>f(x_0)</m> is near zero, which means <m>x_0</m> is near the root and Newton's method will likely converge.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-newton-3-v1" component="proteus">
      <title>Where Newton's Method Fits</title>
      <statement>
          <p>
            Select all situations where Newton's Method would be a reasonable tool.
          </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p>Approximating the solution to <m>\cos(x)=x</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Correct—this equation cannot be solved algebraically but Newton's Method can approximate the solution.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>Finding the exact solution to <m>x^2=9</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Not needed—this equation has an exact solution, so Newton's Method is unnecessary.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p>Programming a calculator or computer to approximate roots efficiently.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>Correct—Newton's Method is fast and widely used in computational root finding.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>Estimating the slope of a tangent line at a point.</p></statement>
          <feedback><p>No—Newton's Method uses tangent slopes, but its goal is to find roots, not slopes.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="chkpt-daniel-question">
      <title>Daniel Question</title>
      <statement>
          <p>
              Given the function <m>f(x)=0.15x^3-0.3x^2-1.8x+2</m> in the interval <m>[-2, 5]</m>, match the behavior of <m>f(x)</m> (left) with the corresponding interval (right).
          </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p></p></feedback>
      <cardsort>
          <match>
              <premise>concave up</premise>
              <response><m>\left(\frac23, 5\right)</m></response>
          </match>
          <match>
              <premise>concave down</premise>
              <response><m>\left(-2, \frac23\right)</m></response>
          </match>
          <match>
              <premise>increasing</premise>
              <response><m>(-2, -1.44) \cup (2.77, 5)</m></response>
          </match>
          <match>
              <premise>decreasing</premise>
              <response><m>(-1.44, 2.77)</m></response>
          </match>
      </cardsort>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-graph-MVT-1-v1">
      <title>PROTEUS EXERCISE</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          There are two methods used by police to enforce speed limits on highways:
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Radar, in which an officer uses a roadside radar gun to measure the speed of a vehicle
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Aircraft patrol, which uses regularly-spaced markings on the highway,
                and measurement from an aircraft of the time it takes a vehicle to travel between markings.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
          Explain, using the [REF] how these two methods are related.
          In particular, if aircraft patrol can only measure average speed,
          how can an officer be certain that a driver was speeding?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>

  </section>

</chapter>